</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Midgut neuroendocrine tumors (MNETs) are rare, and the primary tumor is usually small and difficult to visualize at imaging. Patients often present late with extensive liver and nodal metastases and may experience symptoms secondary to the release of active substances by the primary tumor, such as serotonin and its metabolites, which have local and systemic effects. Locally, this causes desmoplasia and vascular encasement and may lead to small bowel obstruction and ischemia, with significant morbidity and mortality. Systemically, the release of active substances into the circulation can cause flushing, diarrhea, and abdominal pain (carcinoid syndrome); these substances can be detected in urine and blood serum and used as markers for diagnosis and treatment follow-up. MNETs retain expression of specific peptide receptors such as somatostatin receptors, which will bind to synthetic somatostatin analogs such as octreotide. This feature is useful for functional imaging of patients with MNETs and for peptide receptor radionuclide therapy using somatostatin analogs. Resection of the primary tumor is advocated, even in patients with extensive metastases, because it may prevent development of local complications, can help control systemic symptoms, and has been shown to confer some survival advantage. Computed tomography and functional imaging are used to identify the primary tumor and assess its resectability. The main factors governing resectability are patient comorbidities (eg, carcinoid heart disease), vascular involvement, and desmoplasia.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.342135504">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.342135504">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig1.jpeg" height="947" width="799" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Algorithm for imaging evaluation of a suspected MNET. <i>FDG</i> = fluorodeoxyglucose, <i>MR</i> = magnetic resonance, <i><sup>111</sup></i><i>In</i> = indium 111, <i>PET</i> = positron emission tomography, <i><sup>68</sup></i><i>Ga</i> = gallium 68.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig2a.jpeg" height="827" width="818" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Ileal NET in a 66-year-old woman with a mesenteric nodal mass, associated desmoplasia, and liver metastases. <b>(a)</b> Abdominal radiograph from a small bowel series shows desmoplasia (arrow) and separation of the bowel loops. The primary mass cannot be identified. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> portal venous phase CT images show the primary mass (black arrowhead in <b>c</b>), as well as desmoplasia (white arrow in <b>b</b>), mesenteric nodes (white arrowhead in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>), and liver metastases (black arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig2b.jpeg" height="827" width="757" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Ileal NET in a 66-year-old woman with a mesenteric nodal mass, associated desmoplasia, and liver metastases. <b>(a)</b> Abdominal radiograph from a small bowel series shows desmoplasia (arrow) and separation of the bowel loops. The primary mass cannot be identified. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> portal venous phase CT images show the primary mass (black arrowhead in <b>c</b>), as well as desmoplasia (white arrow in <b>b</b>), mesenteric nodes (white arrowhead in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>), and liver metastases (black arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig2c.jpeg" height="719" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span> Ileal NET in a 66-year-old woman with a mesenteric nodal mass, associated desmoplasia, and liver metastases. <b>(a)</b> Abdominal radiograph from a small bowel series shows desmoplasia (arrow) and separation of the bowel loops. The primary mass cannot be identified. <b>(b, c)</b> Coronal <b>(b)</b> and axial <b>(c)</b> portal venous phase CT images show the primary mass (black arrowhead in <b>c</b>), as well as desmoplasia (white arrow in <b>b</b>), mesenteric nodes (white arrowhead in <b>b</b> and <b>c</b>), and liver metastases (black arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig3a.jpeg" height="785" width="786" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> Terminal ileal NET in a 73-year-old man. Coronal portal venous phase CT images obtained with positive oral contrast material (dilute diatrizoic acid [Urografin; BerliMedSA, Madrid, Spain]) <b>(a)</b> and water as the oral contrast agent <b>(b)</b> and CT enterographic image obtained with mannitol contrast agent <b>(c)</b> show a terminal ileal NET (arrow) that is best seen in <b>c</b>, where there is optimal luminal distention. The early phase of contrast agent administration enhances the conspicuity of the hypervascular lesion. Hypervascular liver metastases (arrowhead) also are best demonstrated in <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig3b.jpeg" height="785" width="789" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> Terminal ileal NET in a 73-year-old man. Coronal portal venous phase CT images obtained with positive oral contrast material (dilute diatrizoic acid [Urografin; BerliMedSA, Madrid, Spain]) <b>(a)</b> and water as the oral contrast agent <b>(b)</b> and CT enterographic image obtained with mannitol contrast agent <b>(c)</b> show a terminal ileal NET (arrow) that is best seen in <b>c</b>, where there is optimal luminal distention. The early phase of contrast agent administration enhances the conspicuity of the hypervascular lesion. Hypervascular liver metastases (arrowhead) also are best demonstrated in <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig3c.jpeg" height="772" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> Terminal ileal NET in a 73-year-old man. Coronal portal venous phase CT images obtained with positive oral contrast material (dilute diatrizoic acid [Urografin; BerliMedSA, Madrid, Spain]) <b>(a)</b> and water as the oral contrast agent <b>(b)</b> and CT enterographic image obtained with mannitol contrast agent <b>(c)</b> show a terminal ileal NET (arrow) that is best seen in <b>c</b>, where there is optimal luminal distention. The early phase of contrast agent administration enhances the conspicuity of the hypervascular lesion. Hypervascular liver metastases (arrowhead) also are best demonstrated in <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig4a.jpeg" height="679" width="787" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> MNET in a 63-year-old man. Axial arterial phase <b>(a)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(b)</b> CT images show extensive liver metastases (arrows) that are better demonstrated in <b>a</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig4b.jpeg" height="679" width="787" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> MNET in a 63-year-old man. Axial arterial phase <b>(a)</b> and portal venous phase <b>(b)</b> CT images show extensive liver metastases (arrows) that are better demonstrated in <b>a</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig5a.jpeg" height="698" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> MNET in a 58-year-old man. Coronal T2-weighted <b>(a)</b>, fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(b),</b> and gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> MR enterographic images show the primary tumor (arrow), which is best demonstrated in <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig5b.jpeg" height="698" width="775" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> MNET in a 58-year-old man. Coronal T2-weighted <b>(a)</b>, fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(b),</b> and gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> MR enterographic images show the primary tumor (arrow), which is best demonstrated in <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig5c.jpeg" height="698" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> MNET in a 58-year-old man. Coronal T2-weighted <b>(a)</b>, fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(b),</b> and gadolinium-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted <b>(c)</b> MR enterographic images show the primary tumor (arrow), which is best demonstrated in <b>c</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig6a.jpeg" height="569" width="958" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Terminal ileal NET in a 67-year-old woman. Axial <sup>111</sup>In octreotide scan image fused with corresponding axial CT image <b>(a)</b> and axial fat-saturated gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> show the primary tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig6b.jpeg" height="569" width="917" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Terminal ileal NET in a 67-year-old woman. Axial <sup>111</sup>In octreotide scan image fused with corresponding axial CT image <b>(a)</b> and axial fat-saturated gadolinium-enhanced T1-weighted MR image <b>(b)</b> show the primary tumor (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig7a.jpeg" height="695" width="928" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> MNET in a 53-year-old man. Axial images from <sup>111</sup>In octreotide scan fused with corresponding axial CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and axial images from <sup>68</sup>Ga PET/CT performed 1 month later <b>(c, d)</b> show that the liver metastasis (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) and mesenteric node (arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) demonstrate increased uptake in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>, while the findings are negative in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>. The patient was referred for PRRT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig7b.jpeg" height="695" width="947" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> MNET in a 53-year-old man. Axial images from <sup>111</sup>In octreotide scan fused with corresponding axial CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and axial images from <sup>68</sup>Ga PET/CT performed 1 month later <b>(c, d)</b> show that the liver metastasis (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) and mesenteric node (arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) demonstrate increased uptake in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>, while the findings are negative in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>. The patient was referred for PRRT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig7c.jpeg" height="696" width="947" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> MNET in a 53-year-old man. Axial images from <sup>111</sup>In octreotide scan fused with corresponding axial CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and axial images from <sup>68</sup>Ga PET/CT performed 1 month later <b>(c, d)</b> show that the liver metastasis (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) and mesenteric node (arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) demonstrate increased uptake in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>, while the findings are negative in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>. The patient was referred for PRRT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig7d.jpeg" height="696" width="928" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span> MNET in a 53-year-old man. Axial images from <sup>111</sup>In octreotide scan fused with corresponding axial CT images <b>(a, b)</b> and axial images from <sup>68</sup>Ga PET/CT performed 1 month later <b>(c, d)</b> show that the liver metastasis (arrowhead in <b>c</b>) and mesenteric node (arrow in <b>b</b> and <b>d</b>) demonstrate increased uptake in <b>c</b> and <b>d</b>, while the findings are negative in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>. The patient was referred for PRRT.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig8.jpeg" height="735" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Diagram shows treatment options for patients with an MNET.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig9a.jpeg" height="900" width="581" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> MNET in a 68-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> arterial phase CT images show occlusion of the SMA (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) by an extensive mesenteric nodal mass (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal portal venous phase CT image shows occlusion of the SMV (arrowhead) by the nodal mass (white arrow), with multiple venous collaterals (black arrow). The tumor was considered unresectable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig9b.jpeg" height="901" width="721" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> MNET in a 68-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> arterial phase CT images show occlusion of the SMA (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) by an extensive mesenteric nodal mass (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal portal venous phase CT image shows occlusion of the SMV (arrowhead) by the nodal mass (white arrow), with multiple venous collaterals (black arrow). The tumor was considered unresectable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig9c.jpeg" height="901" width="548" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> MNET in a 68-year-old woman. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> arterial phase CT images show occlusion of the SMA (arrowhead in <b>a</b>) by an extensive mesenteric nodal mass (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal portal venous phase CT image shows occlusion of the SMV (arrowhead) by the nodal mass (white arrow), with multiple venous collaterals (black arrow). The tumor was considered unresectable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig10a.jpeg" height="876" width="570" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> MNET in a 58-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal arterial phase maximum intensity projection (MIP) <b>(a)</b> and curved reformatted <b>(b)</b> CT images show a large mesenteric nodal mass (*) completely encasing the mid SMA (arrow) and its branches. <b>(c)</b> Coronal portal venous phase CT image shows the SMV (arrow) as separate from the mass (*). Because resection would have involved removal of a substantial length of the small bowel, the patient was referred for PRRT rather than for surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig10b.jpeg" height="876" width="456" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> MNET in a 58-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal arterial phase maximum intensity projection (MIP) <b>(a)</b> and curved reformatted <b>(b)</b> CT images show a large mesenteric nodal mass (*) completely encasing the mid SMA (arrow) and its branches. <b>(c)</b> Coronal portal venous phase CT image shows the SMV (arrow) as separate from the mass (*). Because resection would have involved removal of a substantial length of the small bowel, the patient was referred for PRRT rather than for surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig10c.jpeg" height="876" width="824" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> MNET in a 58-year-old man. <b>(a, b)</b> Sagittal arterial phase maximum intensity projection (MIP) <b>(a)</b> and curved reformatted <b>(b)</b> CT images show a large mesenteric nodal mass (*) completely encasing the mid SMA (arrow) and its branches. <b>(c)</b> Coronal portal venous phase CT image shows the SMV (arrow) as separate from the mass (*). Because resection would have involved removal of a substantial length of the small bowel, the patient was referred for PRRT rather than for surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig11a.jpeg" height="871" width="769" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Mid-ileal NET and mesenteric nodes in a 41-year-old man. Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and coronal MIP <b>(b)</b> portal venous phase CT images show the primary tumor located in the mid ileum (black arrow in <b>a</b>), with small, partly calcified local nodes (white arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), extensive liver metastases (arrowhead in <b>b</b>), and no occlusion of major vessels. The tumor was considered resectable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig11b.jpeg" height="871" width="806" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Mid-ileal NET and mesenteric nodes in a 41-year-old man. Sagittal <b>(a)</b> and coronal MIP <b>(b)</b> portal venous phase CT images show the primary tumor located in the mid ileum (black arrow in <b>a</b>), with small, partly calcified local nodes (white arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>), extensive liver metastases (arrowhead in <b>b</b>), and no occlusion of major vessels. The tumor was considered resectable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig12a.jpeg" height="809" width="788" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> MNET in a 58-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and angled sagittal MIP <b>(b)</b> portal venous phase CT images show a large mesenteric node (*). A clear fat plane is seen between the SMA (arrowhead) and SMV (arrow). The tumor was considered resectable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig12b.jpeg" height="809" width="787" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> MNET in a 58-year-old man. Axial <b>(a)</b> and angled sagittal MIP <b>(b)</b> portal venous phase CT images show a large mesenteric node (*). A clear fat plane is seen between the SMA (arrowhead) and SMV (arrow). The tumor was considered resectable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig13a.jpeg" height="689" width="781" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Midgut NET and nodal mass in a 58-year-old woman. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> portal venous phase CT images show vascular encasement, with occlusion of the SMV (black arrow in <b>a</b>), extensive venous collaterals (arrowheads), and encasement of the SMA. The small bowel is thick walled and dilated (white arrow), findings consistent with ischemia. There are few unaffected small bowel loops. The tumor was considered unresectable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig13b.jpeg" height="689" width="794" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Midgut NET and nodal mass in a 58-year-old woman. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> portal venous phase CT images show vascular encasement, with occlusion of the SMV (black arrow in <b>a</b>), extensive venous collaterals (arrowheads), and encasement of the SMA. The small bowel is thick walled and dilated (white arrow), findings consistent with ischemia. There are few unaffected small bowel loops. The tumor was considered unresectable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig14a.jpeg" height="635" width="875" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> MNET and chronic small bowel ischemia in a 66-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> CT images show extensive pneumatosis intestinalis (arrow) and free gas (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig14b.jpeg" height="635" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> MNET and chronic small bowel ischemia in a 66-year-old woman. Axial <b>(a)</b> and coronal <b>(b)</b> CT images show extensive pneumatosis intestinalis (arrow) and free gas (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig15a.jpeg" height="632" width="831" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Mild ileal NET in a 58-year-old woman. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show a NET (arrow in <b>b</b>), a short segment of abnormal thickened small bowel with mesenteric desmoplasia (black arrowhead in <b>a</b>), and a mesenteric node (arrow in <b>a</b>) and surrounding desmoplasia causing the spoke-wheel appearance of the mesentery. Multiple normal loops of small bowel are seen (white arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>).The tumor was considered resectable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig15b.jpeg" height="632" width="844" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Mild ileal NET in a 58-year-old woman. Coronal <b>(a)</b> and axial <b>(b)</b> CT images show a NET (arrow in <b>b</b>), a short segment of abnormal thickened small bowel with mesenteric desmoplasia (black arrowhead in <b>a</b>), and a mesenteric node (arrow in <b>a</b>) and surrounding desmoplasia causing the spoke-wheel appearance of the mesentery. Multiple normal loops of small bowel are seen (white arrowhead in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>).The tumor was considered resectable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig16.jpeg" height="866" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span> MNET in a 52-year-old man. Coronal portal venous phase CT image obtained with positive oral contrast material shows severe desmoplasia (white arrow) and mesenteric nodes (black arrow). Extensive abnormal, dilated, thick-walled small bowel loops are seen (arrowheads). The tumor was considered unresectable because of the insufficient length of unaffected small bowel.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig17.jpeg" height="866" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> MNET in a 38-year-old man. Coronal portal venous phase CT image shows severe desmoplasia (white arrow) and a mesenteric nodal mass (black arrow). Extensive abnormal, dilated, thick-walled small bowel loops are seen (arrowheads), with only a short length of normal small bowel remaining. The tumor was considered unresectable.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig18a.jpeg" height="710" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span> MNET in a 64-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Vertical long-axis balanced steady-state free precession (SSFP) cine MR image of the right heart obtained in diastole shows a restricted tricuspid valve opening (arrow) and liver metastasis (arrowhead). <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis balanced SSFP cine MR images obtained in diastole <b>(b)</b> and systole <b>(c)</b> show tricuspid valve stenosis (arrow) and a central coaptation defect, with relatively little tricuspid valve movement from the diastolic image in <b>b</b> to the systolic image in <b>c</b>. (Case courtesy of Oliver Tann, MBBS, MRCP, FRCR, Great Ormond St Hospital, London, United Kingdom.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig18b.jpeg" height="710" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span> MNET in a 64-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Vertical long-axis balanced steady-state free precession (SSFP) cine MR image of the right heart obtained in diastole shows a restricted tricuspid valve opening (arrow) and liver metastasis (arrowhead). <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis balanced SSFP cine MR images obtained in diastole <b>(b)</b> and systole <b>(c)</b> show tricuspid valve stenosis (arrow) and a central coaptation defect, with relatively little tricuspid valve movement from the diastolic image in <b>b</b> to the systolic image in <b>c</b>. (Case courtesy of Oliver Tann, MBBS, MRCP, FRCR, Great Ormond St Hospital, London, United Kingdom.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.342135504/asset/images/large/rg.342135504.fig18c.jpeg" height="645" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span> MNET in a 64-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Vertical long-axis balanced steady-state free precession (SSFP) cine MR image of the right heart obtained in diastole shows a restricted tricuspid valve opening (arrow) and liver metastasis (arrowhead). <b>(b, c)</b> Short-axis balanced SSFP cine MR images obtained in diastole <b>(b)</b> and systole <b>(c)</b> show tricuspid valve stenosis (arrow) and a central coaptation defect, with relatively little tricuspid valve movement from the diastolic image in <b>b</b> to the systolic image in <b>c</b>. (Case courtesy of Oliver Tann, MBBS, MRCP, FRCR, Great Ormond St Hospital, London, United Kingdom.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.342135504&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Capurso G, Rinzivillo M, Bettini R, Boninsegna L, Delle Fave G, Falconi M. Systematic review of resection of primary midgut carcinoid tumour in patients with unresectable liver metastases. <em>Br J Surg</em> 2012;99(11):1480–1486.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/bjs.8842">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22972490/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Systematic+review+of+resection+of+primary+midgut+carcinoid+tumour+in+patients+with+unresectable+liver+metastases&amp;author=G+Capurso&amp;author=M+Rinzivillo&amp;author=R+Bettini&amp;author=L+Boninsegna&amp;author=G+Delle+Fave&amp;author=M+Falconi&amp;publication_year=2012&amp;journal=Br+J+Surg&amp;pages=1480-1486&amp;doi=10.1002%2Fbjs.8842&amp;pmid=22972490">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Yao JC, Hassan M, Phan A, et al. One hundred years after “carcinoid”: epidemiology of and prognostic factors for neuroendocrine tumors in 35,825 cases in the United States. <em>J Clin Oncol</em> 2008;26(18):3063–3072.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1200/JCO.2007.15.4377">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/18565894/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=One+hundred+years+after+%E2%80%9Ccarcinoid%E2%80%9D%3A+epidemiology+of+and+prognostic+factors+for+neuroendocrine+tumors+in+35%2C825+cases+in+the+United+States&amp;author=JC+Yao&amp;author=M+Hassan&amp;author=A+Phan&amp;publication_year=2008&amp;journal=J+Clin+Oncol&amp;pages=3063-3072&amp;doi=10.1200%2FJCO.2007.15.4377&amp;pmid=18565894">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="r3" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Kaltsas GA, Besser GM, Grossman AB. The diagnosis and medical management of advanced neuroendocrine tumors. <em>Endocr Rev</em> 2004;25(3):458–511.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1210/er.2003-0014">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15180952/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=The+diagnosis+and+medical+management+of+advanced+neuroendocrine+tumors&amp;author=GA+Kaltsas&amp;author=GM+Besser&amp;author=AB+Grossman&amp;publication_year=2004&amp;journal=Endocr+Rev&amp;pages=458-511&amp;doi=10.1210%2Fer.2003-0014&amp;pmid=15180952">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">4.</div><div id="r4" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Horton KM, Kamel I, Hofmann L, Fishman EK. Carcinoid tumors of the small bowel: a multitechnique imaging approach. <em>AJR Am J Roentgenol</em> 2004; 182(3):559–567.</div><div class="external-links"><div c